Check how WPS Office was installed

Run:

which wps

Check APT:

dpkg -l | grep wps

Check Snap:

snap list | grep wps

Check Flatpak:

flatpak list | grep -i wps

If you're not sure how it was installed, run:

which wps
dpkg -l | grep wps
snap list | grep wps
flatpak list | grep -i wps

and share the output. I can tell you the exact uninstall command for your installation.

sifat@Raptor:~$ which wps
/usr/bin/wps
sifat@Raptor:~$ dpkg -l | grep wps
ii  wps-office-custom                                   11.1.0.11733.XA+custom                           amd64        WPS Office, is an office productivity suite.
sifat@Raptor:~$

Your output shows that WPS Office was installed as a .deb package via APT, and the package name is wps-office-custom, not wps-office.

Run these commands:

sudo apt purge wps-office-custom

Then remove any unused dependencies:

sudo apt autoremove --purge

Finally, delete the remaining user configuration and cache:
\

rm -rf ~/.config/Kingsoft
rm -rf ~/.local/share/Kingsoft
rm -rf ~/.cache/Kingsoft
rm -rf ~/.fonts/wps-office

To verify it's completely removed:

which wps
dpkg -l | grep wps

Both commands should produce no output (or which wps should report that wps is not found).

If sudo apt purge wps-office-custom fails, paste the exact error message and I'll help you resolve it.
